picID=96.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What Class got most Bonus from VI ?</span><hr size=1> Bards are neat - I agree with Cuthbert, there is a lot we can do that people are unaware of.<br>
<br>
Bet you didn't know bards can do over 2k damage in a minute with DoT's. <br>
<br>
Did you know I can get a regen of about 45 hp a tick going with two songs?<br>
<br>
I can nearly negate damage done to my group using a rune song, with a shaman or enchanter around to slow. Neat trick, huh?<br>
<br>
I think the strong point of a bard is adaptability. There is very, very little I cannot do, though I don't do most of those things as well as other classes (this is where the druid thing comes in, I think - druids are also a &quot;jack of all trades, master of none&quot; class). It's important to learn what to do in different situations; for instance, I'm doing a lot of different stuff if I'm grouped with a shaman or enchanter. I also need to judge whether my group would be better off with an offensive or defensive boost. If I'm grouped with four warriors and a cleric, you can bet your ass I'm singing haste over cantata, should I have to pick.<br>
<br>
I also agree that a lot of the things we do for a group are subtle. After 50, I started to shift towards making my group as efficient as possible. If you cannot swap instruments in when your songs take effect, and melee the rest of the time, consider not meleeing. Shield of Songs is extremely powerful with a lute out - worth more to your group than your melee damage in most cases.<br>
<br>
Bards are cool, if you know what you're doing. I'll quote Kleg here: &quot;A good bard is worth his weight in plat. A bad one is just a pain in the ass.&quot; If you know the right thing to do given the situation, your group will love you. If not, chances are you're just going to frustrate people.<br>
<br>
